{"title_page": "Bamboo Ridge", "text_new": "{{Infobox journal\n| title         = Bamboo Ridge\n| cover         = \n| editor        = Eric Chock and Darrell H.Y. Lum \n| discipline    = [[Literary journal]]\n| peer-reviewed = \n| language      = \n| former_names  = \n| abbreviation  = Bamboo Ridge\n| publisher     = Bamboo Ridge Press\n| country       = [[United States]]\n| frequency     = \n| history       = 1978-present\n| openaccess    = \n| license       = \n| impact        = \n| impact-year   = \n| website       = http://www.bambooridge.com\n| link1         = \n| link1-name    = \n| link2         = \n| link2-name    = \n| JSTOR         = \n| OCLC          = \n| LCCN          = \n| CODEN         = \n| ISSN          = 0733-0308\n| eISSN         = \n| boxwidth      = \n}}\n\n'''''Bamboo Ridge''''' (in full ''Bamboo Ridge:  Journal of Hawai'i Literature and Arts'') is a Hawaii-based [[Literary magazine|literary journal]] and [[Nonprofit organization|nonprofit]] press. It was founded in 1978 by [[Eric Chock]] and [[Darrell H.Y. Lum]] to publish works by and for the people of [[Hawaii]]. In the [[United States]], ''Bamboo Ridge'' is one of the longest-running small presses, and is one of the oldest in Hawaii.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/03/04/features/story01.html|title=Bamboo Ridge presses on {{!}} starbulletin.com {{!}} Features {{!}} /2008/03/04/|last=Star-Bulletin|first=Honolulu|website=archives.starbulletin.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-28}}</ref> It was named after a popular fishing spot on Oahu.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/03/04/features/|title=starbulletin.com|website=archives.starbulletin.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-28}}</ref>  It currently publishes two volumes a year: a literary journal of poetry and fiction featuring work by both emerging and established writers and a book by a single author or an anthology focused on a special theme. Both the journal and book are available singly or by subscription.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bambooridge.com/aboutus.aspx|title=Bamboo Ridge Press - Journal of Hawai'i Literature and Arts|website=www.bambooridge.com|access-date=2019-05-05}}</ref>\n\n[[Lois-Ann Yamanaka]], [[Lee Cataluna]], [[Rodney Morales]], [[Gary Pak]], and [[Nora Okja Keller]] are among the writers ''Bamboo Ridge'' has published. Yamanaka in particular has credited some of her literary success to the press.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== History ==\nChock and Lum started ''Bamboo Ridge'' in 1978 after they noticed that local authors weren't being published in major literary journals.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.honolulumagazine.com/Honolulu-Magazine/November-2014/35-Years-of-Bamboo-Ridge/|title=A New Generation of Editors Take Over After Founders of Hawai\u2018i\u2019s Premier Literary Press Retire|access-date=2018-05-28|language=en}}</ref> They published four slim volumes every year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/97/06/23/features/story2.html|title=\"Bamboo\" thriving|website=archives.starbulletin.com|access-date=2018-05-28}}</ref> They currently only publish two, an anthology and a single-author collection.<ref name=\":1\"/> As the press grew, so did the size of the volumes.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2014 the press partnered with the [[Hawaii Council for the Humanities]] to offer discounts to middle- and high-school students purchasing their books. This is part of an effort to increase the amount of local literature read in the school system.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://hpr2.org/post/bamboo-ridge-bum-bye-now|title=Bamboo Ridge:  Bum Bye Is Now|last=Tanigawa|first=Noe|access-date=2018-05-28|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThat year, Chock and Lum retired as editors. Since then every issue of the journal has been edited by guest editors.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Awards ==\nIn 2009 the press received an Outstanding Service Award from the [[Association for Asian American Studies]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aaastudies.org/awards-winners/|title=Award Winners {{!}} Association for Asian American Studies|website=aaastudies.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-28}}</ref>\n\n==Book publications==\n\n*Nakano, Jiro, 'Outcry from the Inferno: Atomic Bomb Tanka Anthology'', Honolulu, Hawaii, Bamboo Ridge Press \u00a9 1995 {{ISBN|0-910043-38-8}} [104 pp.&nbsp;103 [[Waka (poetry)|tanka]] by 103 poets]''\n*Wang, Wayne, and Diane Mei Lin Mark, ''Chan is Missing: A Film By [[Wayne Wang]], With Introduction and Screen Notes by Diane Mei Lin Mark'' (Honolulu: Bamboo Ridge Press, 1984), {{ISBN|0-910043-06-X}}. A special issue of ''Bamboo Ridge, The Hawaii Writers' Quarterly'' (the full title at the time), No. 23, Summer 1984.\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*''Reimagining The American Pacific: From South Pacific to Bamboo Ridge and Beyond''. By Rob Wilson. Durham: Duke University Press. 2000. {{ISBN|0-8223-2523-3}} (paper); {{ISBN|0-8223-2500-4}} (cloth)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bambooridge.com Official site]\n*[https://dspace.lib.hawaii.edu/handle/10790/5185 Archive of out of print books and back issues]\n\n[[Category:1978 establishments in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:American literary magazines]]\n[[Category:American annual magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1978]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Hawaii]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox journal\n| title         = Bamboo Ridge\n| cover         = \n| editor        = Eric Chock and Darrell H.Y. Lum \n| discipline    = [[Literary journal]]\n| peer-reviewed = \n| language      = \n| former_names  = \n| abbreviation  = Bamboo Ridge\n| publisher     = Bamboo Ridge Press\n| country       = [[United States]]\n| frequency     = \n| history       = 1978-present\n| openaccess    = \n| license       = \n| impact        = \n| impact-year   = \n| website       = http://www.bambooridge.com\n| link1         = \n| link1-name    = \n| link2         = \n| link2-name    = \n| JSTOR         = \n| OCLC          = \n| LCCN          = \n| CODEN         = \n| ISSN          = 0733-0308\n| eISSN         = \n| boxwidth      = \n}}\n\n'''''Bamboo Ridge''''' (in full ''Bamboo Ridge:  Journal of Hawai'i Literature and Arts'') is a Hawaii-based [[Literary magazine|literary journal]] and [[Nonprofit organization|nonprofit]] press. It was founded in 1978 by [[Eric Chock]] and [[Darrell H.Y. Lum]] to publish works by and for the people of [[Hawaii]]. In the [[United States]], ''Bamboo Ridge'' is one of the longest-running small presses, and is one of the oldest in Hawaii.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/03/04/features/story01.html|title=Bamboo Ridge presses on {{!}} starbulletin.com {{!}} Features {{!}} /2008/03/04/|last=Star-Bulletin|first=Honolulu|website=archives.starbulletin.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-28}}</ref> It was named after a popular fishing spot on Oahu.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/03/04/features/|title=starbulletin.com|website=archives.starbulletin.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-28}}</ref>  It currently publishes two volumes a year: a literary journal of poetry and fiction featuring work by both emerging and established writers and a book by a single author or an anthology focused on a special theme. Both the journal and book are available singly or by subscription.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bambooridge.com/aboutus.aspx|title=Bamboo Ridge Press - Journal of Hawai'i Literature and Arts|website=www.bambooridge.com|access-date=2019-05-05}}</ref>\n\n[[Lois-Ann Yamanaka]], [[Lee Cataluna]], [[Rodney Morales]], [[Gary Pak]], and [[Nora Okja Keller]] are among the writers ''Bamboo Ridge'' has published. Yamanaka in particular has credited some of her literary success to the press.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== History ==\nChock and Lum started ''Bamboo Ridge'' in 1978 after they noticed that local authors weren't being published in major literary journals.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.honolulumagazine.com/Honolulu-Magazine/November-2014/35-Years-of-Bamboo-Ridge/|title=A New Generation of Editors Take Over After Founders of Hawai\u2018i\u2019s Premier Literary Press Retire|access-date=2018-05-28|language=en}}</ref> They published four slim volumes every year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/97/06/23/features/story2.html|title=\"Bamboo\" thriving|website=archives.starbulletin.com|access-date=2018-05-28}}</ref> They currently only publish two, an anthology and a single-author collection.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.honolulumagazine.com/Honolulu-Magazine/November-2014/35-Years-of-Bamboo-Ridge/|title=A New Generation of Editors Take Over After Founders of Hawai\u2018i\u2019s Premier Literary Press Retire|access-date=2018-05-28|language=en}}</ref> As the press grew, so did the size of the volumes.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2014 the press partnered with the [[Hawaii Council for the Humanities]] to offer discounts to middle- and high-school students purchasing their books. This is part of an effort to increase the amount of local literature read in the school system.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://hpr2.org/post/bamboo-ridge-bum-bye-now|title=Bamboo Ridge:  Bum Bye Is Now|last=Tanigawa|first=Noe|access-date=2018-05-28|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThat year, Chock and Lum retired as editors. Since then every issue of the journal has been edited by guest editors.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Awards ==\nIn 2009 the press received an Outstanding Service Award from the [[Association for Asian American Studies]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aaastudies.org/awards-winners/|title=Award Winners {{!}} Association for Asian American Studies|website=aaastudies.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-28}}</ref>\n\n==Book publications==\n\n*Nakano, Jiro, 'Outcry from the Inferno: Atomic Bomb Tanka Anthology'', Honolulu, Hawaii, Bamboo Ridge Press \u00a9 1995 {{ISBN|0-910043-38-8}} [104 pp.&nbsp;103 [[Waka (poetry)|tanka]] by 103 poets]''\n*Wang, Wayne, and Diane Mei Lin Mark, ''Chan is Missing: A Film By [[Wayne Wang]], With Introduction and Screen Notes by Diane Mei Lin Mark'' (Honolulu: Bamboo Ridge Press, 1984), {{ISBN|0-910043-06-X}}. A special issue of ''Bamboo Ridge, The Hawaii Writers' Quarterly'' (the full title at the time), No. 23, Summer 1984.\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*''Reimagining The American Pacific: From South Pacific to Bamboo Ridge and Beyond''. By Rob Wilson. Durham: Duke University Press. 2000. {{ISBN|0-8223-2523-3}} (paper); {{ISBN|0-8223-2500-4}} (cloth)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bambooridge.com Official site]\n*[https://dspace.lib.hawaii.edu/handle/10790/5185 Archive of out of print books and back issues]\n\n[[Category:1978 establishments in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:American literary magazines]]\n[[Category:Annual magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1978]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Hawaii]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bamboo_Ridge"}
{"title_page": "Antipruritic", "text_new": "'''Antipruritics''', also known as '''anti-itch drugs''', are [[medication]]s that inhibit the [[itch]]ing (Latin: ''[[pruritus]]'') often associated with [[sunburn]]s, [[allergic reaction]]s, [[eczema]], [[psoriasis]], [[chickenpox]], [[Fungal infection in animals|fungal infection]]s, [[insect bites and stings]] like those from [[mosquito]]es, [[flea]]s, and [[mite]]s, and [[contact dermatitis]] and [[urticaria]] caused by plants such as [[poison ivy]] ([[urushiol-induced contact dermatitis]]) or [[stinging nettle]].\n\n== Common antipruritics ==\n[[Topical]] antipruritics in the form of [[cream (pharmaceutical)|cream]]s and [[spray (liquid drop)|spray]]s are often available [[Over-the-counter drugs|over the counter]]. The [[active ingredient]]s usually belong to these classes:\n* [[Antihistamine]]s such as [[diphenhydramine]] (Benadryl) and [[Hydroxyzine]] \n* [[Corticosteroid]]s such as [[hydrocortisone]] topical cream, see [[topical steroid]]\n* [[Counterirritant]]s, such as [[Mentha|mint oil]], [[menthol]], or [[camphor]]<ref name=\"Hercogova\">{{cite journal |author=Hercogov\u00e1 J |title=Topical anti-itch therapy |journal=Dermatologic Therapy |volume=18 |issue=4 |pages=341\u20133 |year=2005 |pmid=16297007 |doi=10.1111/j.1529-8019.2005.00033.x}}</ref>\n* [[Local anesthetic]]s such as [[lidocaine]], [[pramoxine]], or [[benzocaine]] in topical creams or lotions\n\nOral antipruritics also exist and are usually [[prescription drug]]s. These can be antihistamines as above<ref>{{cite web |last1=St\u00f6ppler |first1=Melissa Conrad |title=Itch (Itching or Pruritus) |url=https://www.medicinenet.com/itch/article.htm#what_should_i_know_about_itching |website=MedicineNet |accessdate=3 June 2019}}</ref> or:\n* [[Nalfurafine]], an orally-administered, centrally-acting [[\u03ba-opioid receptor]] [[agonist]] approved for [[uremic pruritus]] and effective in [[animal model]]s of other prurituses<ref name=\"Inui2015\">{{cite journal|last1=Inui|first1=Shigeki|title=Nalfurafine hydrochloride to treat pruritus: a review|journal=Clinical, Cosmetic and Investigational Dermatology|year=2015|pages=249\u201355|issn=1178-7015|doi=10.2147/CCID.S55942|pmc=4433050|pmid=26005355|volume=8}}</ref>\n\n== Disputed and questionable antipruritics ==\n* [[Burow's solution]], an astringent aqueous solution of  [[aluminium acetate]], is shown to soothe and to relieve itching.\n* [[Olive oil]]\n* [[Jewelweed]] has been shown to be devoid of any anti-itch activity in several controlled studies <ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Long | first1 = D. | last2 = Ballentine | first2 = N. H. | last3 = Marks | first3 = J. G. | year = | title = Treatment of poison ivy/oak allergic contact dermatitis with an extract of jewelweed. | url = | journal = Am. J. Contact. Dermat | volume = 8 | issue = 3| pages = 150\u20133 | pmid = 9249283 | date = September 1997 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Gibson | first1 = M. R. | last2 = Maher | first2 = F. T. | year = | title = Activity of jewelweed and its enzymes in the treatment of Rhus dermatitis. | url = | journal = J. Am. Pharm. Assoc | volume = 39 | issue = 5| pages = 294\u20136 | pmid = 15421925 | date = May 1950 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Guin | first1 = J. D. | last2 = Reynolds | first2 = R. | year = | title = Jewelweed treatment of poison ivy dermatitis. | url = | journal = Contact Dermatitis | volume = 6 | issue = 4| pages = 287\u20138 | pmid = 6447037 | date = June 1980 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Zink |first=B. J. |author2=Otten, E.J. |author3=Rosenthal, M. |author4=Singal, B |title=The Effect Of Jewel Weed In Preventing Poison Ivy Dermatitis |journal=Journal of Wilderness Medicine |volume=2 |issue=3 |pages=178\u2013182 |id= |year=1991 |url=http://www.wemjournal.org/wmsonline/?request=get-abstract&issn=0953-9859&volume=002&issue=03&page=0178 |accessdate=2008-01-16 |doi=10.1580/0953-9859-2.3.178 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* [[Selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor]] are a class of medicines commonly used for depression, and are also said to be effective in controlling pruritus in a small number of refractory cases.<ref name=\"pmid16112451\">{{cite journal | author=Lee CS, Koo J | title=Psychopharmacologic therapies in dermatology: an update | journal=Dermatologic Clinics | volume=23 | issue=4 | pages=735\u201344 | year=2005 | pmid=16112451 | doi=10.1016/j.det.2005.05.015}}</ref> [[Mirtazapine]], a different type of [[antidepressant]], also has antipruritic effects due to its strong antagonism of the [[H1 receptor|H<sub>1</sub> receptor]].\n* [[Calamine lotion]], containing [[zinc oxide]] and [[iron(III) oxide]], is a traditional remedy for mild itching, such as that typically associated with chicken pox \u2013 although the [[Food and Drug Administration (United States)|U.S. Food and Drug Administration]] has asserted that it has little if any scientific evidence.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/1992/09/09/topi.php |title=American Topics. An Outdated Notion, That Calamine Lotion |accessdate=2007-07-19 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070619004539/http://www.iht.com/articles/1992/09/09/topi.php| archivedate= 19 June 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>Appel, L.M. Ohmart and R.F. Sterner, ''Zinc oxide: A new, pink, refractive microform crystal''. AMA Arch Dermatol 73 (1956), pp. 316\u2013324. {{PMID|13301048}}</ref> Nevertheless, they subsequently recommended applying topical OTC skin protectants, such as calamine, to relieve the itch caused by poisonous plants such as [[poison ivy]], [[poison oak]], and [[poison sumac]].<ref>[https://www.fda.gov/ForConsumers/ConsumerUpdates/ucm049342.htm September 2, 2008 FDA Document] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100716055654/https://www.fda.gov/ForConsumers/ConsumerUpdates/ucm049342.htm |date=July 16, 2010 }}</ref>\n* Paste of [[sodium bicarbonate]] (baking soda) and water, applied topically<ref name=\"Paul Tawrell 2008\">Paul Tawrell, ''Wilderness Camping and Hiking''(Falcon Distribution, 2008), 212.</ref>\n* [[Ammonium hydroxide]] (household ammonia), applied topically<ref name=\"Paul Tawrell 2008\"/>\n* [[Papain]]-based topical creams.\n\n== Home remedies ==\n* Cooling with ice or cold water (usually stops the itch for as long as the ice or cold water is applied){{Citation needed|date=January 2008}}\n* Slightly painful stimulation such as rubbing, slapping, [[scratch reflex|scratching]], or heating based on a [[spinal antagonism]] between [[pain]]- and itch-processing neurons{{Citation needed|date=January 2008}}\n* Pine tree gum applied to the affected areas for short periods of time can help in drawing out the oils and drying the skin. \n* Frequent washing of the affected areas in hot water with a drying soap removes oils that come to the surface as the blisters form and provides temporary relief from itching.\n* Applying emollients to the skin such as [[Baby Oil|baby oil]] or petroleum jelly after showering\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite journal | year = 2006 | title = Frontiers in pruritus research: scratching the brain for more effective itch therapy| url = http://www.jci.org/cgi/content/full/116/5/1174 | journal = Journal of Clinical Investigation| volume = 116 | issue = 5| pages = 1174\u20131185 | doi = 10.1172/JCI28553  | pmid = 16670758| last1 = Paus | first1 = R. | pmc = 1451220}}\n\n{{Major Drug Groups}}\n\n{{Antipruritics}}\n\n[[Category:Antipruritics]]\n", "text_old": "'''Antipruritics''', also known as '''anti-itch drugs''', are [[medication]]s that inhibit the [[itch]]ing (Latin: ''[[pruritus]]'') often associated with [[sunburn]]s, [[allergic reaction]]s, [[eczema]], [[psoriasis]], [[chickenpox]], [[Fungal infection in animals|fungal infection]]s, [[insect bites and stings]] like those from [[mosquito]]es, [[flea]]s, and [[mite]]s, and [[contact dermatitis]] and [[urticaria]] caused by plants such as [[poison ivy]] ([[urushiol-induced contact dermatitis]]) or [[stinging nettle]].\n\n== Common antipruritics ==\n[[Topical]] antipruritics in the form of [[cream (pharmaceutical)|cream]]s and [[spray (liquid drop)|spray]]s are often available [[Over-the-counter drugs|over the counter]]. The [[active ingredient]]s usually belong to these classes:\n* [[Antihistamine]]s such as [[diphenhydramine]] (Benadryl) and [[Hydroxyzine]] \n* [[Corticosteroid]]s such as [[hydrocortisone]] topical cream, see [[topical steroid]]\n* [[Counterirritant]]s, such as [[Mentha|mint oil]], [[menthol]], or [[camphor]]<ref name=\"Hercogova\">{{cite journal |author=Hercogov\u00e1 J |title=Topical anti-itch therapy |journal=Dermatologic Therapy |volume=18 |issue=4 |pages=341\u20133 |year=2005 |pmid=16297007 |doi=10.1111/j.1529-8019.2005.00033.x}}</ref>\n* [[Local anesthetic]]s such as [[lidocaine]], [[pramoxine]], or [[benzocaine]] in topical creams or lotions\n\nOral antipruritics also exist and are usually [[prescription drug]]s. These can be antihistamines as above<ref>{{cite web |last1=St\u00f6ppler |first1=Melissa Conrad |title=Itch (Itching or Pruritus) |url=https://www.medicinenet.com/itch/article.htm#what_should_i_know_about_itching |website=MedicineNet |accessdate=3 June 2019}}</ref> or:\n* [[Nalfurafine]], an orally-administered, centrally-acting [[\u03ba-opioid receptor]] [[agonist]] approved for [[uremic pruritus]] and effective in [[animal model]]s of other prurituses<ref name=\"Inui2015\">{{cite journal|last1=Inui|first1=Shigeki|title=Nalfurafine hydrochloride to treat pruritus: a review|journal=Clinical, Cosmetic and Investigational Dermatology|year=2015|pages=249\u201355|issn=1178-7015|doi=10.2147/CCID.S55942|pmc=4433050|pmid=26005355|volume=8}}</ref>\n\n== Disputed and questionable antipruritics ==\n* [[Burow's solution]], an astringent aqueous solution of  [[aluminium acetate]], is shown to soothe and to relieve itching.\n* [[Olive oil]]\n* [[Jewelweed]] has been shown to be devoid of any anti-itch activity in several controlled studies <ref>D. Long, N. H. Ballentine, J. G. Marks. ''Treatment of poison ivy/oak allergic contact dermatitis with an extract of jewelweed.'' Am. J. Contact. Dermat. 8(3):150-3 1997 {{PMID|9249283}}</ref><ref>M. R. Gibson, F. T. Maher. ''Activity of jewelweed and its enzymes in the treatment of Rhus dermatitis.'' J. Am. Pharm. Assoc. Am. Pharm. Assoc. 39(5):294-6 1950 {{PMID|15421925}}</ref><ref>J. D. Guin, R. Reynolds. ''Jewelweed treatment of poison ivy dermatitis.'' Contact Dermatitis 6(4):287-8 1980 {{PMID|6447037}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Zink |first=B. J. |author2=Otten, E.J. |author3=Rosenthal, M. |author4=Singal, B |title=The Effect Of Jewel Weed In Preventing Poison Ivy Dermatitis |journal=Journal of Wilderness Medicine |volume=2 |issue=3 |pages=178\u2013182 |id= |year=1991 |url=http://www.wemjournal.org/wmsonline/?request=get-abstract&issn=0953-9859&volume=002&issue=03&page=0178 |accessdate=2008-01-16 |doi=10.1580/0953-9859-2.3.178 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* [[Selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor]] are a class of medicines commonly used for depression, and are also said to be effective in controlling pruritus in a small number of refractory cases.<ref name=\"pmid16112451\">{{cite journal | author=Lee CS, Koo J | title=Psychopharmacologic therapies in dermatology: an update | journal=Dermatologic Clinics | volume=23 | issue=4 | pages=735\u201344 | year=2005 | pmid=16112451 | doi=10.1016/j.det.2005.05.015}}</ref> [[Mirtazapine]], a different type of [[antidepressant]], also has antipruritic effects due to its strong antagonism of the [[H1 receptor|H<sub>1</sub> receptor]].\n* [[Calamine lotion]], containing [[zinc oxide]] and [[iron(III) oxide]], is a traditional remedy for mild itching, such as that typically associated with chicken pox \u2013 although the [[Food and Drug Administration (United States)|U.S. Food and Drug Administration]] has asserted that it has little if any scientific evidence.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/1992/09/09/topi.php |title=American Topics. An Outdated Notion, That Calamine Lotion |accessdate=2007-07-19 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070619004539/http://www.iht.com/articles/1992/09/09/topi.php| archivedate= 19 June 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>Appel, L.M. Ohmart and R.F. Sterner, ''Zinc oxide: A new, pink, refractive microform crystal''. AMA Arch Dermatol 73 (1956), pp. 316\u2013324. {{PMID|13301048}}</ref> Nevertheless, they subsequently recommended applying topical OTC skin protectants, such as calamine, to relieve the itch caused by poisonous plants such as [[poison ivy]], [[poison oak]], and [[poison sumac]].<ref>[https://www.fda.gov/ForConsumers/ConsumerUpdates/ucm049342.htm September 2, 2008 FDA Document] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100716055654/https://www.fda.gov/ForConsumers/ConsumerUpdates/ucm049342.htm |date=July 16, 2010 }}</ref>\n* Paste of [[sodium bicarbonate]] (baking soda) and water, applied topically<ref name=\"Paul Tawrell 2008\">Paul Tawrell, ''Wilderness Camping and Hiking''(Falcon Distribution, 2008), 212.</ref>\n* [[Ammonium hydroxide]] (household ammonia), applied topically<ref name=\"Paul Tawrell 2008\"/>\n* [[Papain]]-based topical creams.\n\n== Home remedies ==\n* Cooling with ice or cold water (usually stops the itch for as long as the ice or cold water is applied){{Citation needed|date=January 2008}}\n* Slightly painful stimulation such as rubbing, slapping, [[scratch reflex|scratching]], or heating based on a [[spinal antagonism]] between [[pain]]- and itch-processing neurons{{Citation needed|date=January 2008}}\n* Pine tree gum applied to the affected areas for short periods of time can help in drawing out the oils and drying the skin. \n* Frequent washing of the affected areas in hot water with a drying soap removes oils that come to the surface as the blisters form and provides temporary relief from itching.\n* Applying emollients to the skin such as [[Baby Oil|baby oil]] or petroleum jelly after showering\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite journal | year = 2006 | title = Frontiers in pruritus research: scratching the brain for more effective itch therapy| url = http://www.jci.org/cgi/content/full/116/5/1174 | journal = Journal of Clinical Investigation| volume = 116 | issue = 5| pages = 1174\u20131185 | doi = 10.1172/JCI28553  | pmid = 16670758| last1 = Paus | first1 = R.}}\n\n{{Major Drug Groups}}\n\n{{Antipruritics}}\n\n[[Category:Antipruritics]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:, added 1 PMC", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antipruritic"}
{"title_page": "Fernando Di Leo", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| name               = Fernando Di Leo\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = Fernando Di Leo.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|df=y|1932|1|11}}\n| birth_place        = [[San Ferdinando di Puglia]], [[Italy]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|df=y|2003|12||1932|1|11}}\n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates =  <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| other_names        = \n| ethnicity          =  <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| occupation         = [[Film director]], [[screenwriter]]\n| years_active       = \n| era                = \n| spouse             = \n| partner            =  <!-- (unmarried long-term partner) -->\n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n}}\n\n'''Fernando Di Leo''' (11 January 1932 \u2013 December 2003) was an [[Italy|Italian]] [[film director]] and [[screenwriter|script writer]] born in [[San Ferdinando di Puglia]], [[Italy]]. Fernando di Leo made 17 films as a director and about 50 scripts from 1964 to 1985.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=292}}\n\n==Biography==\nFernando Di Leo was born on 11 January 1932 in [[San Ferdinando di Puglia]].{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=292}} After briefly working in a Rome's film school [[Centro Sperimentale di Cinematografia]], di Leo made his debut as a director as part of the omnibus comedy ''Gli eroi di ieri, oggi, domani'' with his episode titled ''Un posto in paradiso'' ({{translation|A Place in Heaven}}).{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=293}} Following this Di Leo wrote several scripts for Westerns, often uncredited.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=293}} This included work on ''[[A Fistful of Dollars]]'', ''[[For a Few Dollars More]]''.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=293}} Some of his Westerns had uncredited literary sources, such as ''[[Days of Vengeance]]'' which as loosely based on [[Alexandre Dumas]]' ''[[The Count of Monte Cristo]]''.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=293}}\n\nDi Leo was a fan of ''[[film noir]]'' and wanted to make an Italian version of these films.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=293}} Among his first efforts was the script for [[Mino Guerrini]]'s ''[[Date for a Murder]]'' based on [[Franco Enna]]'s novel ''Tempo di massacro'' written in 1955.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=293}} In Di Leo's version, the setting is moved to a contemporary Rome and has elements of contemporary spy films.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=293}} Di Leo worked with Guerrini again on the film ''[[Gangsters '70]]'' which did not do well in the box office.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=293}} Di Leo began directing more of his own films at the time including the [[War film|war film]] ''[[Red Roses for the Fuhrer]]'' and a few erotic films: ''[[A Woman on Fire]]'' and ''[[A Wrong Way to Love]]''.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=293}} From 1969 to 1976, di Leo was able to produce many of his own works with his production company Duania cineproduzioni 70.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=292}} He followed this with a return to ''noir'' with ''[[Naked Violence]]'', a film adapting a novel by [[Giorgio Scerbanenco]], a writer who Di Leo would adapt for several future film productions.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=293}}\n\nDi Leo would make a ''[[giallo]]'' film with ''[[Slaughter Hotel]]'' starring [[Klaus Kinski]] and [[Margaret Lee (English actress)|Margaret Lee]].{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=293}} Following this Di Leo worked on ''[[Caliber 9]]'' and ''[[The Italian Connection]]'' which were both inspired by the writing of Scerbanenco.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=293}} He followed up this film ''[[Il Boss]]'', a film which got Di Leo in trouble with politicians and authorities due he the films display connections between the mafia and the Italy's major party [[Democrazia Cristiana]].{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=293}} Di Leo followed this up with ''[[Shoot First, Die Later]]'' in 1974.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=293}} Di Leo worked through the latter half of the 1970s directing ''[[Mister Scarface]]'', ''[[Kidnap Syndicate]]'', and ''[[Nick the Sting]]''.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=294}} He also wrote scripts for other directors such as [[Romolo Guerrieri]]'s ''[[Young, Violent, Dangerous]]'' and [[Ruggero Deodato]]'s ''[[Live Like a Cop, Die Like a Man]]''.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=294}} Di Leo's last film produced by his company Duania cineproduzioni 70 was ''[[Rulers of the City]]'' in 1976.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=294}} He continued with a few more films after with the ''film noir'' ''[[Blood and Diamonds]]'', the erotic drama ''[[To Be Twenty]]'' and ''[[Madness (1980 film)|Madness]]'' ins 1980.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=294}} \n\nDi Leo worked in television in the 1980s, starting with the television series ''[[L'assassino ha le ore contate]]'', which involved six one-hour long made-for-tv films produced by [[RAI Uno]] which as of 2013 are unreleased.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=294}} Di Leo also made ''The Violent Breed'' and his last film ''[[Killer vs. Killers]]'' towards the mid-1980s.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=294}} ''Killer vs. Killers'' wasn't released theatrically in Italy and only surfaced 20 years later on DVD.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=295}} Di Leo died in December 2003.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=295}}\n\n==Select filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n! width=\"15%\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Title !! width=\"4%\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Year!! colspan=\"4\" scope=\"col\" | Credited as !! width=\"10%\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| Notes !! width=\"1%\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" |{{abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n! width=6% |Director!! width=6% | Screenwriter!! width=6% | Story author !! width=6% | Other\n|-\n\n\n!scope=\"row\"|''Gli eroi di ieri, oggi, domani''\n|1963\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{sfn|Curti|2016|p=293}}<ref>{{cite web|url=h